metadata.name: reborn #209
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METALOEWENSBERG #75
metadata.description:
CENTURY-XXX-METALOEWENSBERG is an homage to Ohne Titel (1969–1970) by Verena Loewensberg.

2 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 128

CENTURY-XXX is a series of software sketches that pay tribute to artists of the 20th century. Each piece is named after a specific artist and reimagines one of their original works through code, often by adding motion, variation, or interactive elements. These sketches don’t replicate the original artworks but instead extend their core ideas into new forms.

By “software sketch,” I mean something more informal than a finished artwork. While some of my projects take months or even years to complete, these sketches are created quickly—often in just a few days. They may be lighter in process, but they’re equally important to me. Sketching with code is how I think through ideas and discover new directions for future work.

The project began with the CENTURY exhibition at DAM Projects in Berlin in fall 2012, where I premiered Network C, Network D, and the first Signal to Noise software piece. Since then, these sketches have inspired more full-scale artworks like METASOTO, METAVASARELY, METAMOLNAR (also known as Hommage à Molnar), including the eponymous CENTURY released through Art Blocks in June 2021.

CENTURY-XXX Series 1 was released from December 2021 to January 2022 in editions of 1,000. The first artwork in Series 2 followed in October 2022, also in an edition of 1,000. The remaining four works in Series 2 are scheduled for release starting in 2025, each in smaller editions of fewer than 128 based on what feels appropriate for the individual piece.

The long-term vision for CENTURY-XXX is to create 100 software sketches, each one inspired by a different artist and artwork from the 20th century.

SERIES 1
1.1 — CENTURY-XXX-METAMETAMALEVICH
1.2 — CENTURY-XXX-METAMOLNAR(S)
1.3 — CENTURY-XXX-METAMORELLET
1.4 — CENTURY-XXX-METARILEY
1.5 — CENTURY-XXX-METAKELLY

SERIES 2
2.1 — CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE
2.2 — CENTURY-XXX-METALOEWENSBERG

More CENTURY-XXX’s to come…

metadata.name: Sano #45
metadata.description:
Using Coronado’s algorithm as a starting point, Sano extends and embraces the notion of beauty existing in imperfection but allows for more impressionistic compositions with less structure, letting something atmospheric and understated emerge with subtle interactions that combine into dissonant chordal expressions infusing a breadth of emotion while maintaining a characteristic timbre.

Just as Coronado referenced a beat-up vintage guitar that had a patina and sound all its own, Sano refers to the vintage amp it was plugged into. A tube-amp from the 1960s with a spring reverb that when combined with single coils and hollow body of the guitar delivered screaming feedback as well as wonderfully gritty warm tones, which this algorithm attempts to echo visually.

There are 100 artist curated outputs in this short-form collection.

Keys:
S : save at current resolution
1 → 6 : save 2000x2500 → 12000x15000
(Chrome recommended for higher resolutions)

our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

metadata.name: monogrid 1.1 CE #99
metadata.description:
Each monogrid artwork gets initialized with a start up algorithm that builds up a set of rectangles and fills them with pixels. There are two different styles, 'Pixel' and 'Line', to create the initial image.

There is a set of 16 animations at work. 4 noise based animations, 4 shifting animations, 4 modulo based animation and 4 reset animations, all run in parallel. Each animation selects a rectangle from the initial setup and edits the pixels in this area. The selection process runs independently and animations can overlap which results in a new style of animation.

monogrid 1.1 is based on the original series at https://monogrid.xyz, but there are no black/white versions included. The color palette is a mixture of one of 12 colors plus black or white.
The fragment shader has been updated in the way the 16 different animations get summed up. This version would appear more chaotic and organic.

monogrid 1.1 - Collectors Edition
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: The Fire Within #159
metadata.description:
This project is a study of ink, everything is generated in code without using any texture. 
It is an attempt to capture the ink bleeding effect and the look of the traditional Chinese paintings that have texts on top with modern approaches.

metadata.name: CityScape: Istanbul #76
metadata.description:
Istanbul is a city that straddles the Bosporus Strait, and lies in both Europe and Asia, with a population of over 15 million residents. Most of the population is located in big iconic hills known as the "Seven Hills of Istanbul". 

   In this project, I tried to capture and interpret the daily life routine of the people who live in these hills with the viewing point from Bosphorus. There are three camera angle possibilities to examine the details in different layers. Also, building types, the slope of the hill, and green area density vary in between those scenarios. There are two time zones: day and night. In the night scene, there is a possibility to obtain the crescent moon which is the symbol of the culture inhabits in these lands.

To save as a high-quality image, open in live view and click yes on the incoming prompt.

Created with p5js

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #5
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

"Axiomatic Pixels" is a generative project that combines my fascination with pixels, glitch art and patterns. Like almost all my pieces, this work was the product of the constant play with these elements. Each hash gives a pattern of pixels combined with paintbrush.
